				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left( {{\alpha} hv} \right)^{n} = C (hv - {E_{\text{g}}} )$$\end{document}where α is the absorption coefficient, hν is the absorption energy, C is a parameter associated with the valence and conduction band, and Eg is the band gap. The digit of n depends on the nature of the transition. In our case, for an indirect band gap, the value of n is 1/2. The variation of (αhν)1/2 with photon energy is shown in Fig. 2b. The band gaps were determined to be about 3.44 eV of TiO2 and 2.61 eV of TiO2/Ag, respectively, by extrapolation of the linear portion of the absorption coefficient α to zero for indirect-band-gap nanoparticles. When the band gap is reduced, the spectral absorption range of TiO2 will be broadened, from only absorbing ultraviolet light originally to visible light. Besides, the yield of photogenerated electron–hole pair will also increase because of the shortening of band gap [44].
